description:
secretx-keyring/src/lib.rs:112-113 (get path) and 156-157 (put path):

```rust
let service = self.service.clone();
let account = self.account.clone();
```

Each call clones two heap-allocated Strings to move them into the spawn_blocking closure. For typical keyring usage frequencies (occasional reads of API keys / credentials at startup or refresh), this is irrelevant. Flagging because the same pattern in a high-frequency code path would matter, and changing struct fields to `Arc<str>` makes the clones zero-cost (refcount bump) without compromising the existing API:

```rust
pub struct KeyringBackend {
    service: Arc<str>,
    account: Arc<str>,
}
// ...
let service = Arc::clone(&self.service);
let account = Arc::clone(&self.account);
```

`keyring::Entry::new` takes `&str`, which works for both `String` and `Arc<str>` via Deref/AsRef.

Expected impact: trivial CPU difference today (two String clones per get/put). Worth doing if/when the read frequency rises (e.g. caching layer added that revalidates per request). Scale impact at current usage: negligible.
